<h2>Event in July 2020</h2>
<br><br>
<h3>Extreme drought in parts of Europe</h3>
July 2020 was drier than normal over large parts of Europe. The driest area with less than 60% of normal precipitation (partly less than 20%) stretched from France through central Europe up to southern parts of European Russia and west Kazakhstan. Most severe deficits with exceptionally below-average precipitation amounts (< 10th percentile, see Figure 14) occurred over France, southern parts of Belgium, Luxembourg, western central parts of Germany, and north of the Caspian Sea. According to the GPCC precipitation index, the July drought in this area was classified as moderate or severe in most parts, in some parts even extreme.
<br><br>
Particularly affected was France. Averaged over the whole area of metropolitan France, the precipitation total was less than 20mm for the whole month, making July 2020 the driest on record since 1959, far ahead of July 1964 and 1979. The area of whole Central Europe as defined in Figure 15 received 80% of the 1981-2020 normal in July 2020, so this was a similar deficit like the July months of the previous years 2018 and 2019. However, we should remember that spring 2020 had already a large deficit in much of Central Europe.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jul2020/Stateofclimate_Jul2020_rr_0_25deg_perc_monthlysums_2020_1981-2010_v20_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_rr_baselayers_overlay_2020-07-31T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2020/Stateofclimate_Jul2020_rr_0_25deg_perc_monthlysums_2020_1981-2010_v20_0e_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_rr_baselayers_overlay_2020-07-31T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jul2020/Stateofclimate_Jul2020_rr_0_25deg_perc_monthlysums_2020_1981-2010_v20_0e_nc__2020-07-31T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2020/Stateofclimate_Jul2020_rr_0_25deg_perc_monthlysums_2020_1981-2010_v20_0e_nc__2020-07-31T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jul2020/Rcc_eude_eur_spi_mean_2020_07.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2020/Rcc_eude_eur_spi_mean_2020_07.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
''Figure 1: Precipitation in July 2020: Percentage of the 1981-2010 average (left) (source: E-OBS), GPCC Precipitation Index (right) (source: DWD).
<br><br>
The dryness in July 2020 was related to temporary heat waves extending from Southwestern Europe occasionally up to Central Europe with especially high daily maximum temperatures (see the sections below). As a result, the relative air humidity became low and the evaporation high. Therefore the soils and some rivers dried out. Water restrictions were imposed in large parts of France and also in parts of Germany. Since it was the third consecutive dry year in parts of Central Europe, the ground water levels decreased, causing regional problems not only for agricultural plants, but also for woods, which became less resilient to bark beetle diseases due to missing water supply.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jul2020/Soil_moisture_3rd_decade_July_2020.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2020/Soil_moisture_3rd_decade_July_2020.png" width="250px"></a>
