<h2>The weather in July 2020</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Temperatures across Europe deviated substantially from their 1981-2010 average in July 2020, with a pattern largely opposite to that in June, associated with a change in the prevailing atmospheric circulation from anticyclonic to cyclonic over Scandinavia. In contrast to the record-breaking warm temperatures reported there for June, it was cooler than average in July, particularly over southern Norway and central Sweden. However, southern Europe was generally warmer than average in July, with very hot conditions over Portugal and south-western Spain, extending south over northwestern Africa. Near-record high temperatures were briefly experienced more widely over southwestern and partly in western Europe under the influence of southerly flow late in the month, with temperatures in France reaching 40 degrees in Paris (see TXx Figure 10). Central and southern Sweden and parts of Norway say very cold conditions for many days in July.
<br><br>
